Looks like that the content provider tries to update an already disposed SWT 
widget. Daniel, can you please look at this. It happens in browsing world.

fViewer.add which causes the disposed exception is enclosed in:
  Control ctrl= fViewer.getControl();
  if (ctrl != null && !ctrl.isDisposed()) {
    ...
  }
Therefore I have no idea why this could happen under normal control flow.

Michael, you also filed bug 42592 which seems to be connected to this one: I
assume that your workbench got into some invalid state somehow.

Can you post the .log.
Can you reproduce the bug?

Build id?

Please reopen with data.

The build was I20030903. The exception was the only thing in the log. I had a 
look at the stack trace and it looks like it is the tree item that is throwing 
the error and not the tree itself so the above coe wouldn't catch that.

Yes, but if adding a new item to a non-disposed TreeViewer from the UI thread
fails then there seems to be a major problem either in the TreeViewer or Tree
code. Furthermore disposing from another thread (e.g. background) is not
possible since this would throw SWT.ERROR_THREAD_INVALID_ACCESS.

Moving to SWT for comment.

You are right.  Another thread could not dispose the item but someone could 
perhaps have done it just before your code ran using asynExec().  It is the 
item that is disposed, not the tree.

Then this is something JFace has to handle. The content provider calls the 
element based add API and doesn't know anything about the tree items 
manipulated.

An asyncExec could not have come in on the item in question because it was 
newly created in the same call to add (in createTreeItem).

One potential hole I can see is that VariablesViewer overrides newItem as 
follows:
	...
	setNewItem(super.newItem(parent, style, index));
	return getNewItem();
	...

So if there was a thread switch between this two statements and somebody called 
setNewItem to a disposed item, then getNewItem would return it.
However, this would cause updateItem to fail, which is called before updatePlus.
updateItem does the work inside a safe runnable, so if there was a failure it 
would not be propagated, but would be logged.

Michael, were there any other entries in the log?

one in the log.

Also, it couldn't have been the VariablesViewer since that does not use a 
JavaBrowsingContentProvider.
